/-
  Data.PDF.Content.Encoding.WinAnsi — the WinAnsiEncoding table

  Ports `Pdf.Content.Encoding.WinAnsi` from Hackage's `pdf-toolbox-content`
  (https://github.com/Yuras/pdf-toolbox, `content/lib/Pdf/Content/Encoding/WinAnsi.hs`,
  fetched from
  `https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Yuras/pdf-toolbox/master/content/lib/Pdf/Content/Encoding/WinAnsi.hs`),
  module 6 of the `pdf-toolbox-content` import documented in
  `docs/imports/PdfToolboxContent/dependencies.md`.

  PDF32000-1:2008 Annex D.2's WinAnsiEncoding: a fixed table mapping
  single-byte character codes (as used by simple fonts) to the Unicode
  character each code represents. Pure data, transcribed verbatim from
  upstream's `zip codes chars` construction (itself built from two separate
  literal lists, recombined here into one list of pairs for clarity).

  ## Design

  Upstream represents the table as `Map Word8 Text`; this port uses
  `Std.HashMap UInt8 Data.Text` (`Data.Text = String`, so Lean string
  literals are used directly for the values — no `encodeUtf8` step is needed,
  unlike the byte-string keys of `Data.PDF.Content.GlyphList`). Upstream's
  `codes` list has no duplicate entries, so `Std.HashMap.ofList`'s
  right-biased duplicate resolution never comes into play.
-/
